diff:1620511488:1620453607:=66,78c66%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-220449-585710#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Non-native speaker's take on replacing adv. with adj. %0a%3c -> - yuluz%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c As a non-native English speaker, I was taught to always use adverbs when describing a verb (eg. doing well, eat quickly) or an adjective (eg. very good, perfectly made). This rule is stuck in my head ever since day one, so whenever I hear people replacing adverbs with adjectives, it rings a bell in my head and sometimes would give me a bit of a cringe. %0a%3c %0a%3c Putting aside my grammar education, I think in conversation American English context, replacing an adverb with an adjective convey a more laid-back and sincere attitude. For example, when someone uses the phrase "real good" when speaking with another person, I think it means that the speaker is loosened up and relaxed around the listener. While if someone uses "really good", it could be that he/she is not very close to the listener and out of politeness it was better to use the complete adverb.%0a%3c %0a%3c At other times, using adjective in place of an adverb can convey a slightly different meaning. In the example of "Today is going slow(ADJ)." vs "Today is going slowly(ADV).", when we say the day is going slow, it is more like the speaker is having a long and tired day. While if we say the day is going slowly, I feel like it is much more literal as if it  means that the day, just like a person, is actually going/walking slowly.  %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-220449-585710#%0a---%0a> %0a
